note.p: This correction is supplied by Cathal Mac Mhuirich himself in the upper margin.
Black (ID0030454) gives the word here as a form of the adjective beo but the present editor things it is a form of the verb attá, tha.
On this form of aer see Ronald Black (1973): 205-06.
Black (1973) gives this as 'fann' but there is clearly a supercript a over the f. I wonder might the missing portion of MS had an i and this might be a form of 'ifern'?

Black (0111317) and (1973, pp.201, 208) notes this as 'rugadh' and nowhere notes that the reading in the MS is is 'slugadh' and that his reading is thus an emendation. The present editor is nonetheless inclined to agree with such an emendation.
I'm note sure about the HW here.
Black (0120113) gives the headword sár- but says this is doubtful.
I am not confident of this HW. Also see RB's note in the HDSG slip. Any suggestions for other HWs necessary.

The edges of the MS page are lost but because of fading (and staining?) it is unclear if there was something witten afer 'sia' and before the current edge of the page. If there was it could be 'dé(u)g'? Although what then are the 26? Looking below: (1) O Neill; (2) O Domhnaill; (3) O Ruairc; (4) Mág Eochagáin; [For ‘con maol muaigh burum dealbna’ see end of note] (5) O Maolseachlainn; (6) O Ragnaill; (7) O Conchubhair Donn; (8) O Concubhair Ruadh; (9) O Máille; (10) O Flaithbeartach; (11) trí mic suibhne. Or, if we’re thinking there is 16, is it (11-14) trí mic suibhne? I don’t quite know how to break up ‘con maol muaigh burum dealbna’. I currently have (a) con maol muaigh; (b) burum dealbna.? Need to do some research on this.
There are two puncta below the t here, however the present editor would not agree with deleting the t.

It sees that there was something written after the arr-abbreviation with the superscript d. There appears to be a descender as far as the (imaginary) line, i.e. to about the same length as the 'do' before 'iarraid', and another descender as long as the long descender of the arr-abbreviation. This may be the remnants of an ar-abbreviation.
This seems to mean including as opposed to something along the lines of 'bestows, conveys, escorts, delivers' given as a translaiton for the verb in eDIL.

The abbreviation here is likely to have been enclosing puncta but as there the writing surface is lost after g can only be noted here as the abbreviation being a single punctum denoting an abbreviation.

Given the scribe's practice so far this is likely to have been intended to be enclosing puncta to indicate the abbreviation. AS is however, the abbreviation has been noted as a single punctum and the abbreviation has been expanded after the g rather than before it.
There is a punctum delens above the suspension stroke here but it is unclear to the present editor how this could fit in here.
